{"key":"processedPost-15359543","value":{"id":15359543,"first":15355144,"last":16150939,"when":1321115308,"utime":"11/12/11 06:28 PM","cleanedPost":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>XLucy in the SkyX said:</strong><br />it is proven that a cold shock induces pinning. the cold temp stops the mycelium from growing within the substrate which helps make the change to fruiting (p. stamets)</blockquote><br />Total absolute disinformation.&nbsp; You seriously need to learn to read what Paul was actually saying.&nbsp; A cold shock is for cold weather, fall-fruiting species, and not for tropical species like <i>P cubensis</i> which fruit during the heat of summer from the tropics to Florida and South Texas.<br />Every grower who has attempted to cold-shock a tropical species has seen his grow either destroyed, or at least set back by two weeks or more.<br />We appreciate people trying to help, but it's important to get some experience by having a few grows under your belt before giving definite answers such as \"it has been proven\", when you're totally off the mark.<br />RR"}}